{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5bf6412-44a8-48ca-b368-dc2e21fd1baa","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively. Since the project has `OutputType: Exe`, use:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis filters the test tree to only the `SmsNotificationTests` class. The `--` separates `dotnet run` arguments from arguments passed to the TUnit executable.\n\nAlternatively, with `dotnet test`:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"04fbc248-fddc-45ca-88c8-02616b83e55c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120). TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. The user wants to run only the `SmsNotificationTests` class.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, the filter syntax uses `--treenode-filter` with a path-based expression. To filter by class name:\n\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nSince TUnit projects use `OutputType: Exe`, you run them with `dotnet run` (not `dotnet test` with VSTest). But actually, with newer versions, `dotnet test` may also work if the MTP integration is set up. Let me think about the correct approach.\n\n\nActually, both `dotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"` and `dotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"` should work with TUnit's MTP setup. The treenode filter path follows the structure `/assembly/namespace/class/test`, so filtering by class name with the wildcard pattern `/**/SmsNotificationTests/**` should capture all tests in that class.","outputTokens":655},"id":"28ad0895-2715-48dc-9e2b-bf4b312124c5","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:25:14.293Z","parentId":"86e63c2b-7706-4110-9f6e-a7e9222f1984"}
